O God! Thou art my God alone;
My soul doth thirst for Thee;
Through desert night, through night unknown,
I seek Thy face, set free.

In dawn's first light I lift my song,
Thy love is better than life;
For in its grace, I do belong,
And find my peace, my wife.

When shadows fall and silence grows,
I meditate on Thee;
Thy presence is my heart's repose,
My soul's sweet harmony.

Thou art my strength, my hiding place,
My shield, my hope, my own;
O God! I seek but Thy dear face—
Thou art my God alone.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
My soul doth thirst for Thee;
Through desert night I seek Thy throne,
Where flows the living sea.

As morning breaks on silent height,
So shines Thy face to me;
No dawn so fair, no starry light,
Can match Thy grace, so free.

Thou art my refuge, strength, and song,
When shadows fill the way;
To Thee my weary heart belongs,
At breaking of the day.

I'll praise Thee through the fading years,
With every breath I own;
O God! Thou art my God, my tears,
My joy, my heart's true home.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
My soul doth thirst for Thee;
Through desert sands I walk, and moan,
In want of rest from Thee.

As morning dew on withered grass,
Thy mercy softly falls;
Thou crown'st my life with holiness,
And life beyond these walls.

When stars grow dim and shadows creep,
Thy voice still calls my name;
No other light shall wake my sleep,
No other love the same.

I'll bless Thee while my heart doth beat,
In joy and in the ache;
For Thou hast been my refuge sweet,
And evermore, my Maker, Thou art my God alone, I take.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
My soul doth thirst for Thee;
Through shadowed vale and arid stone,
I seek where Thou dost be.

In silent dawn, on bended knee,
My heart lifts cries untold;
The night is vast, yet still I see
The whisper of Thy hold.

Thy presence is the morning’s light,
The dew upon the grass;
Thou turn’st my weeping into might,
My mourning into mass.

No idol carved, no fleeting flame,
Can draw me from Thy throne;
For in Thy name I breathe, I am—
I am not mine, but Thine, O Lord, alone.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
My soul doth thirst for Thee;
Through night and desert, I have known
The weight of longing, free.

Thy presence is the morning's glow
That breaks the darkened sky;
No other light can warm me so,
No other voice reply.

In silence, I have sought Thy face,
Through trials deep and long;
Thy mercy is my resting place,
My fortress, and my song.

I'll praise Thee with the break of day,
And till the shadows flee;
O God! Thou art my God alway,
My all, my life, my plea.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
At dawn I seek Thy face;
My soul doth thirst for Thee, my stone,
In desert, time, and space.

I stood where shadows long had crept,
And thought upon Thy name;
The night would weep, the stars would sweep,
And still I called the same.

For Thou art more than morning's glow,
Or songs the angels raise;
Thou art the fountain ever flowing,
The keeper of my days.

When silence falls and fears draw near,
I rest in Thee, my own;
Beneath the shelter of Thy wings,
I'm never more alone.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
No other name I claim.
In breath, in beat, in blood, in bone—
I whisper still Thy name.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
At dawn I seek Thy face;
My soul doth thirst, my flesh doth moan,
For Thy abiding grace.

In desert dry, where shadows creep,
I pondered all Thy ways;
Thee have I loved, in Thee I sleep,
Thy mercies crown my days.

By night I speak, and lift my hands,
Thy praise upon my tongue;
For Thou hast been my help, my strength,
In Thee my heart is young.

So shall I bless Thee while I live,
And lift my hands to Thee;
My soul shall praise, my spirit sing:
Thou art my God—eternally.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
At break of dawn I seek Thy face;
Through desert dry, I groan, I moan,
Yet find in Thee abiding grace.

When shadows stretch and night prevails,
My soul on Thee still calls, still waits;
No other hope my heart avails,
Thy love unlocks the heavy gates.

I wander not in paths astray,
Though trials rise like storm-tossed waves;
Thou art my Guide, my strength each day,
The refuge that my spirit craves.

So let my song through ages run:
No other name, no other throne;
My life, my breath, my hope, my sun—
O God! Thou art my God alone.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
My soul doth thirst for Thee;
Like parched earth by streams once known,
Or restless waves at sea.

At dawn I seek Thy holy face,
In silence cry to Thee;
No fleeting joy, no earthly grace,
Can fill my heart but Thee.

When shadows fall and fears arise,
And starless nights increase,
Thy voice, a light before mine eyes,
Commands the storms to cease.

Thou art my strength, my song, my breath,
The pulse within my breast;
No other name, in life or death,
Shall stand above the rest.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
I’ll praise Thee evermore;
My heart, my soul, to Thee are known—
My Lord, my Life, my Door.

