They build their homes on silent stone,
Where winds dare not intrude;
They long for roots, and call it home,
And name it peace, and good.

But rivers do not choose to rest,
Nor seeds remain in shell;
They break in dark, they seek the light,
And storms give clouds their swell.

The mountain stands, serene and vast,
Yet knows no morning's flame;
While ash takes flight on wayward gusts,
And kindles other plains.

O restless heart, do not be still—
No map is ever drawn;
For only when you lose the path
Do you begin to dawn.

The settled mind forgets the sky;
The answered question sleeps;
But in the tremor, in the cry,
A deeper promise keeps.

So let the ground give way again;
Let every anchor fail;
For only those who drift, unheld,
Shall catch the coming gale.

